<html><head>



<title>

Career and Internship Opportunities

</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor=ffffff><p>


<a name="top">	<!--REFERENCE POINT; TOP OF PAGE-->

<center>

			<!--HEADER GRAPHIC-->

<a href="../images/headbar.map">



<img src="../images/headbar.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 BORDER=0 

alt="The Atlantic Monthly"></a>

</center>
<p>

<br>





<center>

<br>
<br>

<h2>Internships at <i>The Atlantic Monthly</i><br> and <i>Fast Company</i> 
Magazines</h2> <p>


</center

<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>

<center>

<h3><i>The Atlantic Monthly</i>'s Publishing Internship</h3><p>

</center>

<br>


<blockquote>


<i>The Atlantic</i>'s Publishing Internship offers a broad introduction to the
publishing industry.  This internship is offered three times per year: fall
(September - December), spring (January - May), and summer (June - August). We ask
for a minimum commitment of 16 hours/week during the allotted time period. <p>

<p>

The Publishing Internship allows interns to interact with the new media,
special projects, and business departments.  Interns are asked to help with
many different projects, some of which are listed below:<p>



<ul>

<li> Coding magazine articles in HTML in preparation for publishing articles on
our Web site (http://www.theatlantic.com)<p>

<p>

<li> Conducting interviews with magazine authors to accompany the authors' work on
our Web site<p>

<p>

<li>Brainstorming for special-section ideas to propose to advertisers<p>

<p>

<li>Analyzing <i>The Atlantic'</i>s Web site and constructing creative ideas for
new features<p>

<p>

<li>Proofing and fact-checking special advertising sections and coded magazine
articles<p>

<p>

<li>Preparing mailings to promote selected features in our online editions to
members of the media<p>

<p>

<li>Helping with monthly billings<p>

<p>

<li>Performing office-support tasks such as faxing, filing, and answering
phones<p>

</ul>


<p>
<br>
<br>

To apply, please send a resume and cover letter to:	<p>

<br>

Candice White<br>
<i>The Atlantic Monthly</i><br>
77 North Washington Street<br>
Boston, MA  02114<br>
fax: (617) 854-7876<br>
email: candice@theatlantic.com<p>

<br>
<br>

</blockquote>
<hr>
<blockquote>

<br>

<center>

<h3><i>Fast Company</i> Publishing Internship</h3><p>

</center>
<br>
<br>

Become an intern for <i>Fast Company</i>, a non-traditional, new business
magazine published by the owners of <i>U.S. News &amp; World Report</i> and
<i>The Atlantic Monthly</i>.  We offer interships three times per year
(September - December, January - May, and June - August) though we currently
have two <b>immediate openings</b> for the spring semester. Internships require
a minimum commitment of 16 hours/week and a good sense of humor.<p>

<p>

Join our small, somewhat crazy staff and help contribute to our magazine in the
following ways:<p>


<ul>

<li>Research story ideas for editors<p>

<p>

<li>Research factoids to accompany articles in the magazine<p>

<p>

<li>Code magazine articles in HTML in preparation for publishing articles on our
Web site (http://www.fastcompany.com)<p>

<p>

<li>Help promote the <i>Fast Company</i> Web site through establishing reciprocal links,
ad banner swaps, etc.<p>

<p>

<li>Prepare mailings to promote selected features in our magazine and on our Web
site<p>

</ul>


<br>

<br>

To apply, please send a resume and cover letter to:	<p>

<p>
<br>


Candice White<br>
<i>Fast Company</i><br>
77 North Washington Street<br>
Boston, MA  02114<br>
fax: (617) 854-7876<br>
email: candice@theatlantic.com<p>

<br>
<br>

</blockquote>

<hr>

<blockquote>

<br>

<center>

<h3>The Production Internship</h3><p>

</center>

<br>


<i>The Atlantic Monthly</i>, an award-winning national magazine, offers an internship in its Production Department. The

Production Staff organizes the technical aspects of printing the magazine 

and provides support to the Advertising Sales Department. We gather advertising

material to be printed in the magazine, handle the paperwork associated 

with this, and coordinate the layout of each issue. We're seeking organized,

motivated individuals who would like to learn more about magazine 

publishing and layout.<p>


Interns would work on the following projects:<p>


<UL>



<LI>Working with <i>The Atlantic</i>'s Editorial, Art, Ad Sales, and 

Special Projects Departments, you'll produce monthly aides that help us determine 

the layout of the upcoming issue:<p>



	<OL>





		<LI>Maintain a "mock-up" of the magazine on a bulletin board so that all 

at

		<i>The Atlantic</i> can see the initial layout of the magazine and 

comment on

		conflicts (or synergy) they see between ad copy and graphics and art and

		editorial.<p>



		<Li>Assist with the creation, copying, and circulation of a monthly 

issue "dummy"

		that is reviewed by the Production Director, the Publisher, the Senior 

Vice President,

		Ad Director, Art Director, and various editors.<p>



	</OL>

<p>



<Li>Helping our department track advertising information and material:<p>



	<OL>



		<LI>Receive and document materials from advertisers.<p>



		<LI>Maintain advertising information files by advertiser and month.<p>



		<LI>Track, report, and pursue missing advertising paperwork and 

material.<p>



	</OL>



<p>



<LI> General needs:<p>



	<OL>



		<LI>Answer phones.<p>



		<LI>Organize department files and material.<p>

		

	</OL>

	

</UL>		



<p>

The above list is just a partial description of intern responsibilities.<p>



<p>



By the end of the internship, interns will have a broad understanding of

closing and producing a magazine, a working-knowledge of the general 

principles

(and likely pitfalls) of magazine layout and a grasp of standard 

advertising

needs and practices. The internship is unpaid and is available during the 

spring, summer,

and fall. Interns will receive a transportation stipend. We ask for a two- 

to three-day-a-week commitment.<p>

<br>
<br>



To apply, send or fax a cover letter and resume. <b>No 

e-mail submissions, please.</b><p>

<br>

Julia Parker<br>

Production Services Manager<br>

<i>The Atlantic Monthly</i><br>

77 North Washington St.<br>

Boston, MA  02114<br>

fax: (617) 854-7876<P>



</blockquote>

<br>
<br>


