<head>

<title>Literature Index</title>



<meta=atlantic unbound magazine literature poetry books authors reviews 

interviews arts culture commentary essay entertainment politics society>



</head>

<body bgcolor="ffffff">



<!-- HEADER GRAPHIC -->

<center>

<a href="../images/headau.map">

<img src="../images/headau.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 border=0

alt="Atlantic Unbound"></a><p>

</center>



<br>



<a name="literature">





<H2>Literature -- <font size=4><I>Index</I></font></H2>



<p>

<CENTER>

<TABLE BORDER=0 VALIGN=CENTER CELLPADDING=15>

<TR>

<TD WIDTH=50% VALIGN=TOP>





<b><A HREF="./bookauth/baindex.htm">Books & Authors: Interviews and Excerpts</A></b><br> 

Francis Davis, <I>Bebop and Nothingness</I>. William Langewiesche, <I>Sahara Unveiled</I>. Geoffrey Wheatcroft, <I>The Controversy of Zion</I>. Tobias Wolff, <I>The Night in Question</I>. <p><p>







<B><A HREF="./flashbks/west/wesint.htm">Balkan Epic</A></B><br> In 1937 the 

novelist Rebecca West traveled to the Balkans in search of a better 

understanding of that region's historical conflicts.  Her classic account 

of that journey, <I>Black Lamb and Grey Falcon</I>, appeared first in 

<I>The Atlantic Monthly</I> in 1941.  Here are the first three 

installments.  Two more installments will follow.<p>





<B><A HREF="./flashbks/shakes/webintr.htm">Looking for 

Shakespeare</A></B><br>

	

Who <i>really</i> penned the great Shakespeare works?  Here's a look at the 

debate in a special collection of articles from <I>The Atlantic</I>'s pages.<p>





<b><a href="./aandc/Alcott/alcott.htm">Classic Fiction: Louisa May Alcott 

</a></b><br> Until recently, her literary reputation was synomous with 

that of <i>Little Women</i>.  But a very different facet of her work has come 

to light.  Herewith four short stories from <i>The Atlantic Monthly</i> 

that demonstrate Alcott's little-known penchant for romantic fantasy.<p>



</TD>

<TD WIDTH=50% VALIGN=TOP>





<b><A HREF="./factfict/fctfctix.htm">Facts & Fiction</a></b><br> An interview with the author of the short

                           story in <i>The Atlantic</i>'s current issue.<p>



<b><a href="./fiction/recfict.htm">Recent Fiction <br> from <I>The Atlantic 

Monthly</I></a></b><br> A growing anthology of short fiction published in the 

magazine since the launch of the Web edition.<p>



	

<b><a href="./aandc/brfrevs/brevhome.htm">Books: Brief Reviews</a></b><br> 

Consult short takes on contemporary works, delivered each month by <i>The 

Atlantic</i>'s own Phoebe-Lou Adams.<p>





<b><a href="./classrev/crindex.htm">Books: Classic Reviews</a></b><br> How 

did <i>The Atlantic </i> review Charles Dickens's <i>Great Expectations 

</i> in 1861?  What did Virginia Woolf have to say about the novels of E.M.  

Forster in 1927?  Peruse reviews of classic fiction from <i>The 

Atlantic</i>'s storied past.<P>





</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>



</CENTER>



