<html>

<head>



<title>Flashbacks Archive</title>



<meta=atlantic unbound magazine history politics society  news current affairs arts 

culture commentary essay entertainment literature poetry>



</head>



<body bgcolor=ffffff>



<!-- HEADER GRAPHIC -->



<CENTER>

<a href="../images/headau.map">

<img src="../images/headau.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 border=0

alt="Atlantic Unbound"></a><p>

</CENTER>

<br>





<CENTER>

<H1>F<font size=5>LASHBACKS</font> </H1>

</CENTER>



<p>



<blockquote>



<i>The following (in reverse chronological order) are Flashbacks that have

appeared in the online edition of </i>The Atlantic Monthly.<p>



<br>



<blockquote>



<blockquote> 









<font size=4><b>1/97</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/assist/assist.htm">Death, Legal 

and Illegal</a></b><br> The issue of doctor-assisted suicide has at last 

reached the Supreme Court.  In this 1974 <I>Atlantic</I> article Catholic 

theologian Daniel Maquire about the legal and moral ramifications of "mercy 

killing."<p>







<font size=4><b>12/96</b> <A 

HREF="./flashbks/army/army.htm">Reinventing the 

 Military</a></b><br> Explorations, both past and present, of the 

 military's efforts to redefine itself in a rapidly changing world.<p>







<font size=4><b>12/96</b> <A 

HREF="./flashbks/xmas/chrintro.htm">Ghosts of Christmases 

 Past</a></b><br> Three Christmas stories published in <I>The Atlantic</I> 

 near the turn of the century.<p>







 <font size=4><b>12/96</b> <A HREF=" ./cullen/cmjesus.htm">The Historical 

Jesus</a></b><br> In the December, 1986 cover story, titled "Who Do Men Say 

That I Am?", Cullen Murphy surveyed trends in the study of the "historical 

Jesus" and found scholarship that "is among the least antiquarian of historical 

or theological pursuits."<p>





<font size=4><b>11/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/rwanda/rwanda.htm">Central 

Africa</a></b><br> Several past articles put the most recent Rwandan 

refugee crisis in perspective and evaluate various approaches to offering 

assistance and intervention.<p>





<font size=4><b>11/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/crime/crime.htm">Crime and 

Punishment</A></b><br> The crime rate is the lowest it's been in years.  

Are we finally conquering the problem?  Or are we about to experience the 

biggest crime wave yet?<p>







<font size=4><B>10/96 </b><A 

HREF="./flashbks/picasso/picasso.htm">Portraits of Picasso</A></B></font><BR>



Picasso was a dominating presence in twentieth-century art.  The same was 

true for his 

personal relationships, as is shown in the new Merchant-Ivory film <i>Surviving 

Picasso</i>.  <i>The Atlantic</i> has run three cover-story profiles of 

Picasso over the years -- in 1957, 1964, and 1988 -- all of which we've 

gathered here.  <p>



<font size=4><B>10/96 </b><A 

HREF="./flashbks/fall/fall.htm"><i>Atlantic</i> Autumn</A></B></font><BR>

Autumn is again upon us, bringing fresh 

delight in woodsmoke, hot cider, tart apples, colorful foliage, and crisp 

cold air.  <i>Atlantic</I> contributors have waxed poetic about the season 

over the years, and we thought you'd enjoy a fall sampler. <p>





<font size=4><B>9/96 </b><A HREF="./flashbks/Kurds/kurds.htm">Who Are 

the Kurds?</A></B></font><BR>



The Kurds and "the Kurdish question" are in the news a lot lately.  Revisit 

articles from past years on the Kurds by Robert Kaplan (1987) and Laurie 

Mylroie (1992) for context.<p>





<font size=4><B>8/96 </b><A HREF="./flashbks/olympic/olympic.htm">The '96 

Olympics</A></B></font><BR>



In "High Hurdles and White Gloves" an athlete of the First Olympiad 

recounts the spectacle that was the Athens Games of 1896.<p>











<font size=4><B>7/96 </b><A HREF="./flashbks/saudiara/saudiara.htm">Oil and 

Turmoil</A></B></font><BR>



The recent bombing in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, may force

the United States to rethink its level of engagement in the unstable Middle 

East.  Three <I>Atlantic</I> authors tackle the issues of politics, oil, and the 

Persian Gulf.<p>





<font size=4><B>6/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/hillman/schloss.htm">Honors: 

"In the Strawberry Fields"</A></font><br>

	

Eric Schlosser's November, 1995, article on migrant farmworkers in the 

California strawberry industry received a prestigious Sidney Hillman 

Foundation award for magazine writing.  Here's the article, along with 

Schlosser's remarks upon accepting the award.<p>





<font size=4><B>6/96 </b><A HREF="./flashbks/tobacco/tobacco.htm">Can The 

Tobacco Industry Regulate Itself?</A></B></font><BR>



The nation's largest tobacco manufacturer has said it will join the fight 

to prevent underage smoking in exchange for one thing: autonomous 

regulation.  A 1965 article shows why this is an all-too-familiar 

tactic.<p>



<font size=4><B>6/96 </b><A 

HREF="./flashbks/piracy/Piracy.htm">Property Pirates</A></B></font><br>

	

As the U.S. government reproves China for its disrespect of 

intellectual-property rights, we may do well to remember that our own past 

record in that area has been less than impeccable.<p>





<font size=4><B>5/96 </b><A HREF="./flashbks/species/ploverin.htm">Natural 

Selections?</A></B></font><br>

	

With limited resources, how do we decide which species to protect?  And 

does protecting one species justify harming another?  These questions of 

"stewardship" were addressed in a 1992 <I>Atlantic</I> article by Charles 

Mann and Mark Plummer.<p>



	

<font size=4><b>4/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/immigr/immigint.htm">Immigration: The 

Perpetual Controversy</A></font><br> A collection of articles from the 

beginning of the century and from the 1990s shows that immigration -- and 

how to deal with it -- has long been an American preoccupation.<p>





<font size=4><b>4/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/shakes/webintr.htm">Looking for 

Shakespeare</A></font><br>



Who <i>really</i> penned the great Shakespeare works?  Here's a look at the 

debate in a special collection of articles from <I>The Atlantic</I>'s pages.

<p>





<font size=4><b>4/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/FGM/fgmint.htm">Female Genital 

Mutilation</A></font><br>



Nineteen-year-old Fauzia Kasinga made the headlines when she sought asylum 

in this country to avoid female genital mutilation in her homeland of Togo.  

An October, 1995, <i>Atlantic</i> article discussed the prevalence of FGM 

in the United States and described one woman's crusade to combat it.

<p>



<font size=4><b>3/96</b>  <A HREF="./flashbks/xsci/xsci.htm">Prayer vs. Pills</A>

</font><br>



The Supreme Court recently upheld a ruling against a Christian-Scientist 

couple whose diabetic son died when they denied him insulin treatment.

Should parents be held liable for the failure of prayer to heal a 

dangerously ill child? An April, 1995, article by Caroline Fraser considered 

this question.

<p>



<font size=4><b>3/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/China/chinaint.htm">One 

China?</A></font><br>

	

Taiwan has affirmed its commitment to democracy in the face of Beijing's 

saber-rattling.  Where do U.S.  interests lie?  We look back at U.S.-China 

relations during the past century, with articles by John K.  Fairbank, 

Orville Schell, and others.

<p>



<font size=4><b>3/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/MidEast/Mideast.htm">The Middle East: 

Peace in Jeopardy?</A></font><br>



<I>Atlantic</I> articles from 1969, 1985, and 1993 help put hopes for 

Middle East peace in historical perspective.

<p>



<font size=4><b>2/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Black/blahisin.htm">Black History 

Month</A></font><br>



A collection of articles by and about African-Americans, including 

contributions by Frederick Douglass, Booker T. Washington, and W.E.B. 

DuBois.

<p>



<font size=4><b>2/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/pres/presintr.htm">Presidents' 

Day</A></font><br>



A look at Washington, Jefferson, and Lincoln--three presidents whose 

legendary stature has inspired contributions to <i>The Atlantic</I> since 

the magazine's inception.  <p>



<font size=4><b>2/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Death/Deathint.htm">Who Deserves to 

Die?</A></font><br>



The Oscar-winning film <I>Dead Man Walking</I> raises questions about the 

death penalty that have been addressed repeatedly in <I>The Atlantic 

Monthly</I>. Revisit articles by George Bernard Shaw, Irving R.  

Kaufman, and others.  <p>



<font size=4><b>1/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/ftax/FTax.htm">Flat-Tax Proposals</A></font><br>



Steve Forbes's recent proposal for a flat income tax sparked heated debate.  In 

August, 1952, the Dean of Harvard's Law School warned against a similar 

plan that was then before Congress.  <p>





<font size=4><b>1/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/west/wesint.htm">Balkan 

Epic</A></font><br>



In 1937 the 

novelist Rebecca West traveled to the Balkans in search of a better 

understanding of that region's historical conflicts.  Her classic account 

of that journey, <I>Black Lamb and Grey Falcon</I>, appeared first in 

<I>The Atlantic Monthly</I> in 1941.  Here are the first three 

installments.  Two more installments will follow.<p>





<font size=4><b>1/96</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/snow/snowint.htm">Snow</A></font><br>



<i>Atlantic</i> Managing Editor Cullen Murphy looks at the crucial and 

largely unrecognized roles that snow plays in our lives.  <p>



<font size=4><b>12/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/xmas/Chrintro.htm">Ghosts of 

Christmases Past</A></font><br>



A Christmas Eve poem and three Christmas stories published in <i>The 

Atlantic</i> at around the turn of the century.

<p>



<font size=4><b>12/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/blacked/aaedintr.htm">African-American 

Education</A></font><br>



A sampling of <i>Atlantic</i> articles from the 1890s to the 1990s that have 

discussed the education and empowerment of African-Americans. 

<p>



<font size=4><b>12/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Ireland/IrIntro.htm">Ireland: 

Twentieth-Century Witnesses</A></font><br>



A collection--featuring two autobiographical essays by Conor Cruise 

O'Brien and an article on the children of Ulster by Robert Coles--that 

traces the story of Ireland's troubles in this century.  <p>





<font size=4><b>11/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Nurember/Nurem.htm">The Nuremberg 

Trials</A></font> <br>



Two articles from 1946 consider the precedent set at Nuremberg 

fifty years ago.  <p>



<font size=4><b>11/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/israel/rabinint.htm">The State of 

Israel</A></font><br>



Articles from 1949 to 1993, by David Ben-Gurion and others, look at various

	aspects of the spiritual and national project that is Israel.

<p>



<font size=4><b>10/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Budget/Budgint.htm">Balancing the 

Budget</A></font><br>



Can it be done?  Should it be done?  Writings on these questions from the 

past sixty years.  <p>



<font size=4><b>10/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/OJ/ojintrof.htm">The Trial of the 

Century?</A></font> <br>



The O.J.  Simpson trial may have been the media event of the decade, but 

was it the "trial of the century"?  In 1927 the Sacco-Vanzetti verdict 

sparked international protest and raised questions that are still timely.  

A collection of articles on Sacco-Vanzetti and the American legal system.  

<p>



<font size=4><b>8/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/smoking/smoke.htm">Should We Outlaw 

Smoking?</A></font><br>



Articles dating back to 1860 rhapsodize about the joys of smoking, lament 

the difficulties of quitting, point to the correlation between smoking and 

lung cancer, and explain why we smoke in the first place.  <p>



<font size=4><b>8/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Balkans/balk.htm">The Balkan 

Conflict</A></font> <br>



Two authors, one in 1913 and the other in 1989, paint uncannily similar 

pictures of the troubled region, while three articles from the 1960s offer 

glimpses of Yugoslavia's hard-won stability under Tito.  <p>





<font size=4><b>7/95</b> <A HREF="./aandc/gardens/gardhome.htm">A Century of 

Gardens</A></font> <br>



Four 

articles from different time periods discuss the pleasures of gardens and 

gardening.<p>



<font size=4><b>7/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/media/media.htm">Media Mergers</A></font> <br>



In the late 1960s, during a flurry of media-industry mergers, <i>The 

Atlantic</i> published several articles that asked, Who controls the media?  

and How big is too big?  <p>



<font size=4><b>7/95</b> <A HREF="./aandc/Alcott/alcott.htm">Louisa May 

Alcott</A></font><br>



Until recently, her literary reputation was synomous with 

that of <i>Little Women</i>.  But a very different facet of her work has come 

to light.  Herewith four short stories from <i>The Atlantic Monthly</i> 

that demonstrate Alcott's little-known penchant for romantic fantasy.<p>





<font size=4><b>7/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/computer/tech.htm">The Technological 

Revolution</A></font><br> 



These visionary articles--by Vannevar Bush (1945) and 

Martin Greenberger (1964)--heralded the online revolution at the dawn of 

the computer age.  <p>



<font size=4><b>5/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/affact/affact.htm">Affirmative 

Action</A></font><br>



Is affirmative action "reverse racism"?  McGeorge Bundy, Stanley Fish, and 

others offer differing viewpoints.  <p>





<font size=4><b>5/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Taxes/budg.htm">Can We Afford a Tax 

Cut?</A></font><br>



How much tax relief can we afford?  It's not a new question.  See articles 

culled from the past five decades, including Lester Thurow's "Getting 

Serious About Tax Reform" (1981).<p>





<font size=4><b>5/95</b> <A HREF="./flashbks/Welfare/welf.htm">The Welfare 

Debate</A></font><br>



Welfare "as we know it" may be headed for extinction.  Two articles, 

including Irving Kristol's 1971 treatment of the subject, offer past 

perspectives.  <p> 



<font size=4><b>3/95</b><A Href="./aandc/movies/movhome.htm">The Decline of 

Film?</a></font><br> Movie critics Pauline Kael and Michael Sragow comment on 

the state of the art.<p>





<br>

<br>



</blockquote>

</blockquote>



