</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H2>
<font size=7>P</font>OETRY <font size=7>P</font>AGES
</H2>

<I>Updated December 2, 1996</I><p>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<hr size=1>
<br>
<br>


Mingle with other aficionados of the written and 
spoken word, in the <A 
HREF="http://gtwy.theatlantic.com/webboard/$webb.exe/f14"><B>Arts & Literature</B></A> conference of <B>Post & Riposte</B>, <I>The Atlantic</I>'s  
interactive forum.  (<A HREF="../../p&r/p&rhelp.htm">New users</A> enter 
here.)<p>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

</center>
								<!--TEXT-->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<br>

<font size=4>

<font size=5><B><A 
HREF="./antholog/aaindx.htm">An Audible Anthology</A></B></font><br>

<img src="../../images/new.gif" width=40 height=15 hspace=2 vspace=2 
border=0> A new reading by Linda Bierds.  Plus, Stanley Kunitz, Robert Pinsky, Jane Hirshfield, Donald Hall, Linda Pastan, Stephen Sandy, and many others, read their poems from <I>The Atlantic</I>.<p>


<font size=5><B><A HREF="./atlpoets/poetindx.htm">Atlantic Monthly Poetry 
Online</A></B></font> <br>

A collection of poetry published in <I>The 
Atlantic Monthly</I> since the launch of the online edition in November, 
1993, including poems by Richard Wilbur, Maxine Kumin, Jane Kenyon, W. S. 
Merwin, Philip Levine, Galway Kinnell, and many others.<p>


<BLOCKQUOTE>
<hr size=1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


<font size=5><B><A HREF="poetint.htm">The Matter of Poetry</A></B></font><br>
The question 
"Can Poetry Matter?" is as provocative now as it was in May, 1991, when Dana 
Gioia asked it in <I>The Atlantic Monthly</I>. You can read Gioia's article and 
his follow-up to it, "Hearing From Poetry's Audience."<p>



<BLOCKQUOTE>
<hr size=1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


<font size=5><B><A HREF="./frost/frostint.htm">Robert Frost in <I>The Atlantic 
Monthly</I></A></B></font><br>

In his new introduction Peter Davison, <I>The Atlantic</I>'s current poetry 
editor and a friend of Frost's in the poet's last years, tells the story of 
Frost's first publication in the magazine, in 1915.  Here are Frost's first 
three poems to appear in <I>The Atlantic</I>, and one that got 
away, with new readings by Davison recorded recently in Boston.<P>

<font size=5><b><a href="../aandc/dante/danthome.htm">Dante & 
Co.</a></b></font><br>

Dante Alighieri, Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, and Robert 
Pinsky--together in cyberspace.  Hear Pinsky read excerpts from his recent 
translation of the <i>Inferno</i>.  Plus, read the transcript of Pinsky's 
online conference with <I>The Atlantic Monthly</I>, in which he discusses 
poetry, computers, and translating Dante.<p>




<font size=5><B><A HREF="./emilyd/edintro.htm">Emily Dickinson 
(Un)discovered</A></B></font><br>

In 1891, shortly after the posthumous publication of Emily Dickinson's 
poetry, Thomas Wentworth Higginson recalls his correspondence with the 
reclusive poet and reproduces many of her letters and early poems.  <p>

<font size=5><B><A HREF="./whitman/walt.htm">Reminiscences of Walt Whitman 
(1902)</A></B></font><br>

A memoir by John Townsend Trowbridge, who recounts his friendship
 with the bard from Brooklyn and considers Whitman's unique place 
in American literature.<p>


<font size=5><B><A HREF="./nov1857/nov1857.htm">Volume One, Number One -- 
November, 1857</A></B></font><br>

These poems by Ralph Waldo Emerson, Henry Wadsworth 
Longfellow, James Russell Lowell, and John Greenleaf Whittier, appeared in 
<I>The Atlantic Monthly</I>'s first issue.<p>

<br>
<br>



