<title>

Letter from Cullen Murphy

</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor=ffffff>



<p>

<a name="top">	<!--REFERENCE POINT; TOP OF PAGE-->

<center>







			<!--HEADER GRAPHIC-->



		<a href="../images/headbar.map">

<img src="../images/headbar.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 BORDER=0 

alt="The Atlantic Monthly"></a>





</center>



<br>

<font size=3><b>CULLEN MURPHY<br>



Managing Editor</b></font><p>







<p>

<br)

<p>

October 20, 1995<p>



<blockquote>



<p><br><p><br>



<font size=5>W</font><font size=4>elcome to the World Wide Web site of <i>The Atlantic Monthly</i> magazine.<p>



<p>



All forms of communication are a marriage of content and medium, and the

interplay between the two necessarily evolves over time. Even in its long

incarnation--138 years this month--as an object printed on paper, the magazine

has metamorphosed in appearance in many ways, as all magazines do. In the

second half of the nineteenth century advertising was added to <i>The

Atlantic</i>'s pages. In the twentieth century illustrations began to

supplement the printed text and to adorn the cover. The size of the magazine

grew from that associated with a literary journal to that associated with

mainstream general-interest magazines. Content, too, has changed, with more

emphasis on in-depth reporting and analysis of public affairs to complement the

magazine's traditionally strong literature and criticism.<p>



<p>



<i>The Atlantic Monthly</i> on the World Wide Web represents yet another

natural progression, as we strive to make the contents of the print magazine as

easily accessible as possible to as many people as possible. In many respects

there can be no real substitute for the print magazine itself, as far as it

goes; the basic technology, like that of books, seems as admirably suited to

the needs of the human form as are trousers or gloves. But the words "as far as

it goes" are important: electronic media obviously can do a great many things

that print alone cannot. <i>The Atlantic</i> on the Web, we hope, will offer

ample demonstration of that fact, while maintaining the same high standards

that our print readers have come to expect.<p></blockquote>





<img src="./signat.gif" alt="Cullen Murphy" align=right></a>



<br clear=right>

</font>

<br>

<hr>



<font size=1>

Copyright &copy; 1995 The Atlantic Monthly Company.  All rights reserved.

</font>

<p>

<center>

