alt="Daily Quote">



<font size=4><b><i>January 14 - 21, 1997 </i></b></font><p>



<br>



<b>1/15</b> "The pornographer Larry Flynt is probably not the sort of person that Hamlet is thinking of when he muses, 'What a piece of work is man, how noble in reason, how infinite in faculties,' and so on, but Flynt is undeniably a piece of work."<p>



<font size=2> --  <b>Terrence Rafferty</b>,  "Solid Flesh,"</A> <i>The New Yorker</i>, January 13, 1997.</font><p>



<br>



<CENTER>

<B>* * *</B>

</CENTER>



<p>





<b>1/14</b> "All the neurons in the brain that make up perceptions and emotions operate in a binary fashion. We can someday replicate that on a machine. <nobr>. . .</nobr> Eventually we'll be able to sequence the human genome and replicate how nature did intelligence in a carbon-based system. <nobr> . . . </nobr> It's like reverse-engineering someone else's product in order to solve a challenge."<p>



<font size=2> --  <b>Bill Gates</b>, as quoted by Walter Isaacson in <A HREF="http://pathfinder.com/@@Pku7fQQATW1C2evK/time/gates/cover0.html">"In Search of the Real Bill Gates,"</A> <i>Time</i>, January 13, 1997.</font><p>



























