<title>



July 1996 Contributors



</title>

</head>



<body bgcolor="ffffff">

<a name="top">	<!--REFERENCE POINT; TOP OF PAGE-->

<center>





			<!--HEADER GRAPHIC-->

<a href="../../images/headbar.map">

<img src="../../images/headbar.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 BORDER=0 alt="The Atlantic Monthly">

</a>





</center>





<p>



			<!--RUBRIC and DATE-->

<font size=5>Contributors</font><i> -- July 1996</i>



<pre>





</pre>

<blockquote>

	

	<!--LIST OF AUTHORS-->

	

	<B><a name="Cronin">Brian Cronin</A></B> (<a 

	href="./Coverbg.gif">"Cover Art"</a>), is an illustrator who lives in 

	New York City.  His work has appeared in <i>Time</i>, <i>The New York 

	Times</i>, and <i>The New Yorker</i>.<p>



	<B><a name="Davis">Francis Davis</A></B> (<a 

	href="./Young/Young.htm">"Like Young"</a>), a contributing editor of 

	<i>The Atlantic,</i> is the author of <i>The History of the Blues</i> 

	(1995) and <i>Bebop and Nothingness</i> (1996), a collection of 

	essays.<p>



	<B><a name="Fallows">Deborah Fallows</A></B> (<a 

	href="./spa/spa.htm">"Buffed and Polished"</a>), has written for 

	<i>National Geographic</i>, <i>The Washington Monthly</i>, and <i>The 

	Los Angeles Times Magazine</i>.  <p>



	<B><a name="Graham">Mary Graham</A></B> (<a 

	href="./satelite/satelite.htm">"High Resolution, Unresolved"</a>), is a 

	lawyer and writer who lives in Washington, D.C.<p>



	<B><a name="Holland">Brad Holland</A></B> (<a 

	href="./Holland/Holland.htm">"Express Yourself: It's Later Than You 

	Think"</a>), an artist, has received gold medals from 

	the Art Directors Club of New York and the Society of Publication 

	Designers.  His article in this issue appears in somewhat different 

	form in the book <i>Illustration America</i>, to be published this 

	month by Rockport Press.  <p>



	<B><a name="Kaminer">Wendy Kaminer</A></B> (<a 

	href="./Angels/Angels.htm">"The Latest Fashion in Irrationality"</a>), 

	is a contributing editor of <i>The Atlantic</i> and a public-policy 

	fellow at Radcliffe College.  Her essay collection <i>True Love 

	Waits</i> was published last spring.<p>



	<B><a name="Kino">Carol Kino</A></B> (<a 

	href="./salons/salons.htm">"Living-Room Galleries"</a>), is a former 

	New York correspondent for the British quarterly <i>Modern 

	Painters</i>.  She has written about art for <i>The New York Times</i>, 

	<i>Artnews</i>, and <i>Art &amp; Auction</i>.<p>



	<B><a name="Koning">Hans Koning</A></B> (<a 

	href="./germania/germania.htm">"Germania Irredenta"</a>), is at work on 

	a novel, <i>Night and Day</i>, to be published next year.<p>



	<B><a name="Levine">Robert A. Levine</A></B> (<a 

	href="./depress/Clinton.htm">"The Economic Consequences of Mr.  

	Clinton"</a>), a senior economist emeritus at the Rand Corporation, was 

	deputy director of the Congressional Budget Office from 1975 to 

	1979.<p>



	<B><a name="Lux">Thomas Lux</A></B> (<a 

	href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/Lux/houses.htm">"He Has Lived in 

	Many Houses"</a>), teaches writing at Sarah Lawrence College and is the 

	author of <i>Split Horizon </i>(1994).  <p>



	<B><a name="Mayers">Florence Cassen Mayers</A></B> (<a 

	href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/Mayers/sestina.htm">"All-American 

	Sestina"</a>), is a poet whose work has appeared in <i>The Paris 

	Review, Epoch</i>, and <i>Poetry</i>.  <p>



	<B><a name="Palley">Thomas I. Palley</A></B> (<a 

	href="./depress/depress.htm">"The Forces Making for an Economic 

	Collapse"</a>), teaches economics at the New School for Social 

	Research, in New York City.  He is the author of <i>Post Keynesian 

	Macroeconomics</i>, to be published this year.<p>



	<B><a name="Rubin">Richard Rubin</A></B> (<a 

	href="./Grant/Grant.htm">"Welcome to Our Tomb"</a>), has recently been 

	published in <i>The New Yorker, </i>the<i> Oxford American,</i> and 

	<i>The Southern Review</i>.  <p>



	<B><a name="Stark">Steven Stark</A></B> (<a 

	href="./gender/gender.htm">"Gap Politics"</a>), writes about politics 

	and popular culture and is a commentator on National Public Radio.  <p>



	<B><a name="Thompson">Charles Thompson</A></B> (<a 

	href="./McInern/McInern.htm">"Robert Penn McInerney"</a>), is the 

	fiction and book editor of <i>American Way</i> magazine.  He has 

	written for <i>Spy, Mademoiselle</i>, and <i>The Oregonian</i>.  <p>



	<B><a name="Walters">Mark Walters</A></B> (<a 

	href="9607fict/spring.htm">"Spring"</a>), teaches literature and 

	creative writing at William Jewell College, in Liberty, Missouri.<p>

	



</blockquote>



												



