<blockquote>
	
	<!--LIST OF AUTHORS-->
	
<B><a name="Belieu">Erin Belieu</A></B> (<a 
href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/belieu/passed.htm">"Passed 
On"</a>), is the author of <I>Infanta</I> (1995), a 
collection of poems. Her work has appeared in <I>The New York Times</I> 
and <I>Agni</I>.<p>

<B><a name="Bochner">Paul Bochner</A></B> (<a 
href="./hopper/hopper.htm">"Someplace Like Home"</a>), is a painter who lives near New York 
City. He has won several international awards for his short films.<p>

<B><a name="Edsall">Thomas Byrne Edsall</A></B> (<a 
href="./protean/protean.htm">"The Protean President"</a>), a political reporter for 
<I>The Washington Post</I>, is the author of <I>Chain Reaction</I>, 
written with Mary D. Edsall (1991).<p>

<B><a name="Gaetano">Nicholas Gaetano</A></B> (<a 
href="contents.htm">cover art</a>), is an illustrator and abstract painter who 
lives in North Carolina. His work has been widely exhibited in the United 
States and Japan.<p>

<B><a name="Hall">Donald Hall</A></B> (<a 
href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/hall/couple.htm">"The Wedding 
Couple"</a>), is the author of <I>Their Ancient Glittering Eyes</I> (1992) 
and <I>The Museum of Clear Ideas </I>(1993).  Hall's poem in this issue 
will appear in his book <I>The Old Life: New Poems</I>, to be published 
next month.<p>

<B><a name="Pennington">Debra Pennington</A></B> (<a 
href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/penning/post.htm">"Postscript"</a>), teaches English at the University of 
Alaska at Anchorage. Her poems have appeared in <I>Hellas</I> and 
<I>Shaping the Landscape</I>.<p>

<B><a name="Peterson">Peter G. Peterson</A></B> (<a 
href="./aging/aging.htm">"Will America Grow Up Before It Grows Old?"</a>), is the 
chairman of The Blackstone Group, a private investment bank. A book based 
on his article in this issue will be published in September by Random 
House.<p>

<B><a name="Plumly">Stanley Plumly</A></B> (<a 
href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/plumly/trees.htm">"The Marriage in the Trees"</a>), is a professor of English at 
the University of Maryland at College Park. His poem in this issue will 
appear in a new collection of the same title, to be published this 
fall.<p>

<B><a name="Portis">Charles Portis</A></B> (<a 
href="./9605fict/9605fict.htm">"I Don't Talk Service No More"</a>), is a novelist and 
journalist who lives in Arkansas. His books include <I>True Grit</I> 
(1968) and <I>Gringos</I> (1991).<p>

<B><a name="Reiss">James Reiss</A></B> (<a 
href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/reiss/cycle.htm">"Cycle"</a>), is a professor of English at Miami University, in 
Oxford, Ohio, and the editor of Miami University Press. His books include 
<I>Express</I> (1983) and <I>Parable of Fire</I> (1996).<p>

<B><a name="Tymoczko">Dmitri Tymoczko</A></B> (<a 
href="./nitrous/nitrous.htm">"The Nitrous Oxide Philosopher"</a>), is a teaching assistant 
at Harvard University.<p>

<B><a name="Ward">Thom Ward</A></B> (<a 
href="../../atlweb/poetry/antholog/ward/vasect.htm">"Vasectomy"</a>), is a poet whose work has appeared in <I>Poetry 
Northwest</I>, <I>Yellow Silk</I>, and <I>The Christian Science 
Monitor</I>.<p>


<B><a name="Wheatcroft">Geoffrey Wheatcroft</A></B> (<a 
href="./ireland/ireland.htm">"In Tune With Ireland"</a>), is a columnist for <I>The 
Daily Express</I> of London and the author of the forthcoming <I>The 
Controversy of Zion</I>.<p>

<B><a name="Youngren">William H. Youngren</A></B> (<a 
href="./clementi/clementi.htm">"Finished Symphonies"</a>), is a professor of English at 
Boston College.<p>


	

</blockquote>

